File: platform/browser-extension/src/network-capture.ts

The chrome.debugger.onEvent listener (line 171) handles Network.requestWillBeSent, Network.responseReceived, Network.loadingFailed, Network.loadingFinished, Network.webSocketCreated, Network.webSocketFrameSent, Network.webSocketFrameReceived, and Runtime.consoleAPICalled.

Missing: Network.webSocketClosed handler. When a WebSocket connection closes, CDP fires Network.webSocketClosed with { requestId, timestamp }. The handler should delete state.wsFramesByRequestId.get(requestId) to free the entry.

Pattern to follow (from the existing handlers):
```
} else if (method === 'Network.webSocketClosed') {
    const requestId = paramsRecord?.requestId as string | undefined;
    if (requestId) {
      state.wsFramesByRequestId.delete(requestId);
    }
}
```

Place this after the webSocketFrameSent/webSocketFrameReceived block (after line ~340) and before the Runtime.consoleAPICalled block.

The wsFramesByRequestId map (line 93) maps requestId → WebSocket URL. It is populated on webSocketCreated (line 305) and read on frame events (line 326). Currently it is only cleared on getWsFrames(clear=true) (line 509) or stopCapture (line 445). Without cleanup on close, entries for closed WebSocket connections persist for the entire capture session.
